(c)    Each worst-case release scenario and alternative release scenario, including without limitation, administrative controls and mitigation measure taken to limit the distances to the endpoint for each scenario;

The Worst-Case release scenario involves the release of 14,000 pounds of anhydrous ammonia over a 10 minute period which would result due to a failure of the Control Pressure Receiver.  This quantity is considered in the event that (for some reason) the entire system charge would be A?pumped downA? into the Control Pressure Receiver and the Control Pressure Receiver should rupture.  Pressure vessels are never to be filled to more than 80% or 85% or their capacity and the 14,000 pounds is based on 100% of the vessel.  Under this Worst-Case scenario and the prescribed A?staleA? air and wind conditions, ammonia could travel 1.6 miles before dispersing enough to no longer pose a hazard to the public.

The Worst-Case rlease scenario is highly unlikely for the following reasons:

A?    The Worst-Case weather conditions which were used for this scenario are uncommon;
A?    Industry and ASME standards were followed for the manufacture and quality control of the High Pressure Ammonia Receiver.  U-1A manufacturerA?s data reports and State Permit will be on file the facility;
A?    The Control Pressure Receiver is located inside the Engine Room and cannot be impacted by a vehicle.  The Engine Room is kept locked and cannot be accessed except by authorized personnel;
A?    Ammonia is not corrosive in this service and the Control Pressure Receiver will be maintained in good condition and inspected at least annually by the personnel and every 4 years by the insurance carrier or by the State;
A?    Dual safety relief valves limit operating pressure in the Control Pressure Receiver; and
A?    The facility will have a training program designed to ensure that the system is operated by experienced and qualified personnel.

Several alternative (more likely) release scenarios at the facility involve the following:

A?    Release of 504 pounds over a period of 8 hours due to a A?pinA? hole in a pipe on the roof.  The ammonia lines will be painted or insulated to prevent rusting or corrosion and inspected annually.
A?    Release of 1090 pounds over a period of 60 minutes due to a flange gasket leaking at one of the connections at a solenoid valve or strainer located on the roof.
A?    Release of 138 pounds over a one minute period due to the rupture of the ammonia receiving hose during the a charging of the system.

None of the above alternate scenarios would pose a hazard to the public at a distance of more that .1 miles.

The likelihood of an alternative release scenario is minimized for the following reasons:

